                            <comment id="14368863" author="ay" created="Thu, 19 Mar 2015 11:02:39 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I am not sure if this is a real problem.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Why 400 needs to be treated differently from other 4xx?&lt;br/&gt;
The reason why 500 is treated differently by default is that this is the code that is used  when returning a SOAP fault.&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ws-i.org/profiles/basicprofile-1.1-2004-08-24.html#R1126&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;http://www.ws-i.org/profiles/basicprofile-1.1-2004-08-24.html#R1126&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;But you can always override this behavior (e.g., making SOAP faults returned with other code processed) by setting the following context property at the client.&lt;br/&gt;
org.apache.cxf.transport.no_io_exceptions&lt;/p&gt;
</comment>
                            <comment id="14368984" author="jbliznak" created="Thu, 19 Mar 2015 12:20:48 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;CXF supports SOAP 1.2 and this spec lists 400 as allowed too: &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/soap12-part2/#http-respbindprocess&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;http://www.w3.org/TR/soap12-part2/#http-respbindprocess&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14369462" author="ay" created="Thu, 19 Mar 2015 15:00:05 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;My interpretation was that the server may return a SOAP fault with http 400 in SOAP 1.2 to indicate the client error, but this is not an application soap fault that is processed and mapped back to the corresponding fault.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I am not sure whether changing this behavior to process the HTTP 400 SOAP faults may introduce a regression in some BP 1.x. SOAP 1.1 related TCK tests. BP 2.0 does seem to give any hint on the correct behavior. If things are okay, we can decide how to introduce this feature. (i.e. active for both soap 1.* or only for 1.2, etc).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Someone else also wants to comment?&lt;/p&gt;
</comment>
                            <comment id="14711837" author="asoldano" created="Tue, 25 Aug 2015 19:35:17 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;So, given there&apos;re still doubts on this, I believe the best approach is to do what follows:&lt;br/&gt;
1) add an option for allowing processing responses on HTTP 400 response code&lt;br/&gt;
2) externalize the response code processing to a separate protected method that can easily be overridden.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Attached you find a patch for doing that (and actually reading properties only when needed). Unless someone see a valid reason for not going this way, I&apos;ll commit the patch in the next days.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14712812" author="ay" created="Wed, 26 Aug 2015 09:33:01 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Alessio,&lt;br/&gt;
thanks for following up on this topic.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;so, are we going to set this property to true automatically for soap 1.2 and false for soap 1.1 at the client? &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I am not sure if I we should just instead handle 400 for soap 1.2 directly and avoid introducing another property.&lt;br/&gt;
One can always overwrite this default behavior by turning on the current no_io_excpetion option.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;regards, aki&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14712861" author="asoldano" created="Wed, 26 Aug 2015 09:59:20 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;To grant backward compatibility I&apos;m not changing the default behaviour for now, so the prop will default to false (not set).&lt;br/&gt;
If we want to change the default behaviour (say, in next minor), I&apos;m fine with that.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
